Here are the variables included and their meanings:

  • track: Track name
  • type: Single or three lap record
  • shortcut: Shortcut or non-shortcut record
  • player: Players name
  • system_played: Used system (NTSC or PAL)
  • date: World record date
  • time_period: Time as hms period
  • time: Time in seconds
  • record_duration: Record duration in days

Question 2

Return the count of cases where a record was broken in more than a year (365 days).

library(dplyr)
records %>% 
  filter( record_duration > 365 ) %>%

Question 3

Return name of the player, name of the track, record date, and record duration for the record that took the longest time to be broken.

library(dplyr)
longestDuration <- records %>%
  arrange(desc(record_duration)) %>%
  slice(1)
playerResult <- longestDuration %>%
  select(player, track, date, record_duration)
playerResult
##   player        track       date record_duration
## 1 Alex G Yoshi Valley 2010-11-27            3659

Question 4

Return the mean record time (time) by each track. What is the name of the track with the fastest average record time? Hint: you should use `group_by() and summarize()

library(dplyr)
trackMean<-records %>%
  group_by(track) %>%
  summarize(meanTime = mean(time))
fastest <- trackMean %>%
  filter(meanTime == min(meanTime))
fastest

Question 7

Continuing with your results in Question 6: Do you notice a trend across years? Are the record times getting faster, slower, or no clear pattern in time? Create a barplot where each year appears on the x axis (you can treat year as a categorical variable in this case) and y axis showing the mean record time in each year. Interpret your graph. Hint: Use your code in Question 6, which returns the average record times by year, followed by %>% ggplot(aes(year,mean)) + geom_bar(stat='identity') Hint2: To make your figure wider, you can insert fig.width=10 inside the curly brackets at the beginning of your r code chunk below, as {r, fig.width=10} which I already did for you below,

library(ggplot2)
avg <- records %>%
  group_by(year) %>%
  summarize(meanTime=mean(time))
avg %>%
  ggplot(aes(year, meanTime)) + geom_bar(stat="identity") + 
  labs(x = "year", y= "Mean Record Time") + ggtitle("Mean Record Time by Year") + ggtitle("Mean Record Time by Year") + theme_minimal()

Question 8

Create two overlaid histograms by type on the same plot where each histogram shows the distribution of time for a given track type. Combine dplyr and ggplot2 to achieve this. How do record times compare between Single Lap and Three Lap tracks? Hint: use records %>% dplyr functions %>% ggplot(., aes()) + type of ggplot plot to combine dpylr with ggplot. Note that the dot inside ggplot() is a placeholder for records, as dplyr has already pulled records df at the beginning of the code (making it unnecessary to type it twice!)

Note: Set alpha=.5 for transparency.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
records %>%
  ggplot(aes(time,fill=type)) + geom_histogram(alpha=0.5, bins=30) + labs(x="Time", y="Frequency") + ggtitle("Distribution of Record Times by Type") + scale_fill_manual(values=c("Single Lap"="blue", "Three Lap"="red")) + theme_minimal()

Question 9

Three Lap time reports the total time spent finishing three laps in total, as opposed to finishing a single lap. Lets divide all time observations with type=="Three Lap" by 3 to check whether per lap performance declines across Three Lap vs.Single Lap. Generate a new variable named time_per which is the time spent per round, and create two overlaid histograms of type_per by type. Hint: Use mutate(), and inside mutate() use ifelse() function to conditionally replace rows: e.g.., ifelse(type=="Three Lap",time/3,time) which divides time by three only if type=="Three Lap".

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)

  records <- records %>%
  mutate(time_per = ifelse(type == "Three Lap", time / 3, time))
  
  records %>%
  ggplot(aes(time_per, fill = type)) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.5, bins = 30) +
  labs(x = "Time per Lap", y = "Frequency") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of Time per Lap by Track Type") +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("Single Lap" = "blue", "Three Lap" = "red")) +
  theme_minimal()

# Question 10 There appears to be recent discoveries of shortcuts within some of the tracks causing a number of extraordinarily fast records set in Three Lap tracks (Have you noticed this in your graph in Question 9?). Replicate your histogram in Question 9 with shortcut=="No" filter.

library(dplyr)
library(ggplot2)
records %>%
  filter(shortcut == "No") %>%
  ggplot(aes(time, fill = type)) +
  geom_histogram(alpha = 0.5, bins = 30) +
  labs(x = "Time", y = "Frequency") +
  ggtitle("Distribution of Record Times by Track Type (No Shortcut)") +

Question 11

Lastly, compare the mean time by system_played. Do you observe a difference across the two game systems? (Note: NTSC version of the game runs at 60 FPS (Frames Per Second), and PAL runs at 50 FPS!) Does this appear to affect performance of records set?

library(dplyr)
timeComparison <- records %>%
  group_by(system_played) %>%
  summarize(meanTime = mean(time))
timeComparison
## # A tibble: 2  2
##   system_played meanTime
##   <chr>            <dbl>
## 1 NTSC              79.9
## 2 PAL               95.2

There is a difference in performance between the two game systems. Records in the NTSC system have faster times compared to the PAL system on average which likely allows players to complete races more quickly. Hence, time frame difference may appear to affect the performance of records sets.
